''See also [[aguë]]''
==English==

===Etymology===
Middle English [[ague]] and Old English [[agu]], [[ague]], from Old and Middle French [[aguë]] ([[fievre]]), "acute (fever)", from Late Latin ([[febris]]) [[acuta]] "acute fever", from [[acutus]] "sharp, acute" + [[febris]] "fever".

===Pronunciation===
* ''US:'' {{IPA|/əˈgju/, /ʌˈgju/}}, {{SAMPA|/@"gju/, /V"gju/}}

===Noun===
'''ague''' (''plural'' '''[[agues]]''')
# {{obsolete}} An acute [[fever]]. 
#* Brenning agues. —P. Plowman.
# {{pathology}} An [[intermittent]] fever, attended by alternate cold and hot fits.
# The cold fit or [[rigor]] of the intermittent fever; as, ''fever and ague.''
# A chill, or state of [[shake|shaking]], as with cold.

====Quotations====
*'''1969''': [[w:John Kennedy Toole|John Kennedy Toole]], ''[[w:A Confederacy of Dunces|A Confederacy of Dunces]]'', p. 200.
*: He had to capture some character and get out of that rest room before his '''ague''' got so bad that the sergeant had to carry him to and from the booth every day.

===Verb===
{{en-infl-reg-other-e|agu|e|}}
# {{transitive}} To [[strike]] with an ague, or with a cold [[fit]].

